  "prompt": "What is the difference between '-' and '-=' operators in C++?",
  "response": "In C++, the `-` and `-=` operators serve different purposes when used in expressions:\n\n1. **Subtraction Operator `-`:**\n   - The `-` operator is a binary arithmetic operator used to subtract one operand from another.\n   - It takes two operands (e.g., `a - b`) and returns the result of subtracting the second operand (right side) from the first operand (left side).\n   - Example:\n     ```cpp\n     int a = 10;\n     int b = 3;\n     int result = a - b; // result is 7\n     ```\n\n2. **Subtraction Assignment Operator `-=`:**\n   - The `-=` operator is a compound assignment operator that subtracts the right operand from the left operand and then assigns the result back to the left operand.\n   - It effectively combines the subtraction operation and the assignment operation into one.\n   - Example:\n     ```cpp\n     int a = 10;\n     int b = 3;\n     a -= b; // a is now 7, equivalent to a = a - b;\n     ```\n\nIn summary, the `-` operator is used simply to subtract two values, while the `-=` operator performs subtraction and updates the left-hand operand with the result of the operation.",
